(Voice of Germany Chinese) Studies by a team of international scientists show that ice and snow in the Himalayas are accelerated. According to the assessment of the International High Mountain Development Center (ICIMOD) located in Kandu, Nepal, in the 2010s, the melting speed of ice and snow in the region increased by 65%compared with the previous decades.

"We are losing glaciers, and these glaciers will no longer exist after 100 years," said the center's environmental scientist and reporter Philippus Wester.

Xingdu Kush/Himalayas stretch 3,500 kilometers, crossing 8 countries in Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, China, India, Myanmar, Nepal and Pakistan.

The report pointed out that if the temperature increases by 1.5 degrees Celsius to 2 degrees Celsius compared with the previous industrialization era, by 2100, the glaciers in the entire region will lose 30%-50%of its original volume.

